[{"id":"VR930961","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows 3 labeled figures. Figure 1 is an energy level diagram, and figures 2 and 3 are corresponding spectra. In Figure 1, at the top, the Energy Level Diagram shows four horizontal lines at different energy levels. From top to bottom, the energy levels are described as follows. The highest level is labeled 5 E sub 0. The next level is labeled 2 E sub 0. The following level is labeled E sub 0 and the lowest level is labeled 0. Below the energy level diagram, the first spectra is shown and labeled Figure 2, and below that the second spectra is shown and labeled Figure 3. Each spectrum is plotted along a horizontal axis labeled Frequency, and the values 0 through 5 f sub 0, in increments of f sub 0, are indicated. In the Figure 2, vertical lines are indicated above f sub 0, 2 f sub 0, and 5 f sub 0. In Figure 3, vertical lines are indicated above f sub 0, 2 f sub 0, 3 f sub 0, 4 f sub 0, and 5 f sub 0.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR930961.g02.svg\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> represents some energy states of a hypothetical, single-electron atom.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Figures <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> each represent part of the emission spectrum for a hypothetical atom consisting of a nucleus and a single electron. For figures <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\">\\(E_0=hf_0\\)</span>.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following indicates whether Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> or Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> corresponds to the energy states in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> and provides a valid justification?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR930961_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, because the emission spectrum contains all nonzero frequencies that correspond to all nonzero energy states.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, because the emission spectrum contains all frequencies that correspond to all energy differences between the lowest energy state and a different energy state.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>, because the emission spectrum contains all frequencies that correspond to the energy differences between all pairs of energy states.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>, because the emission spectrum contains the frequency and integer multiples of that frequency that correspond to the energy difference between the lowest energy state and the adjacent energy state.</p>"],"answer":2}]